\\n\\n2. **If user never returns**: The session stays ENDED, the shadow branch has the trailing conversation, but it's never condensed to `entire/checkpoints/v1` and never pushed. The data exists only locally on the shadow branch.\\n\\n\\n3. **markSessionEnded** just transitions state to ENDED — no condensation, no push.\\n\\nSo the core issues are: trailing conversation after the last commit either gets misattributed to the next checkpoint or disappears entirely if the user doesn't return, and the remote never sees this data unless there's another commit cycle. I'm considering a few approaches to fix this, starting with pushing the shadow branch during the stop hook so the trailing conversation gets persisted remotely even if the session ends.\\n\\nAlternatively, I could condense and push during the stop hook by updating the existing checkpoint with the trailing conversation data, which would keep everything semantically correct and get the remote in sync — though this would require changing how condensation works to support amending existing checkpoints rather than always creating new ones.\\n\\nOr I could create a separate trailing checkpoint linked to the previous one, keeping things cleanly separated but adding complexity to the web UI for understanding the relationship.\\n\\nAnother option is to update the last checkpoint in-place during the stop hook by reading its existing data, appending the trailing conversation, and writing it back — this preserves correct attribution but requires careful handling of concurrent scenarios.\\n\\nI think updating the existing checkpoint is the cleanest approach. Since checkpoints are stored at sharded paths in the git tree, I can just overwrite the files at that location using the existing `WriteCommitted` operation. The main thing I need to figure out is adding a push call to the Stop hook, since pushing currently only happens in PrePush.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":740,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":37428,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":740},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYmM7kUQ6g3NdBPntn7Jy\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"b01b4178-1eed-4484-9e21-b19b7224b561\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T06:24:32.828Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"b01b4178-1eed-4484-9e21-b19b7224b561\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/4\",\"sessionId\":\"26fd10e5-9929-4364-b5e7-540290e8931b\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/stop-hook-updates-remote-checkpoints\",\"slug\":\"composed-humming-rocket\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01J6tyStarpZoyiypghBT65U\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have the full picture. Here's what I've confirmed:\\n\\n## Confirmed Problems\\n\\n1. **Trailing conversation misattribution**: If user commits again later, `ENDED + GitCommit` fires `ActionCondenseIfFilesTouched` — the trailing conversation from session N gets condensed into checkpoint N+1. It semantically belongs to checkpoint N.\\n\\n2. **Data loss if user never returns**: Session stays ENDED, shadow branch has the trailing conversation locally, but it's never condensed to `entire/checkpoints/v1` and never pushed. Data is stranded on local shadow branch forever.\\n\\n3. **Stale remote**: Web UI shows the checkpoint as it was at push time (step 4 in your flow). The post-commit trailing conversation is invisible remotely.\\n\\n4. **`markSessionEnded` does nothing with checkpoints** — it only transitions the state machine to ENDED and sets `EndedAt`. No condensation, no push.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Proposed Approaches\\n\\n### Approach A: Update the last checkpoint on Stop hook\\n\\nOn the Stop hook (after `SaveStep` writes trailing conversation to shadow branch):\\n1. Look up the last checkpoint ID from the most recent commit's `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer\\n2. Read the existing checkpoint from `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n3. Update it with the complete transcript (trailing conversation included)\\n4. Write it back to `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n5. Push `entire/checkpoints/v1` to remote\\n\\n**Pros**: Correct attribution — trailing conversation belongs to the checkpoint that produced it. Single source of truth. Web UI sees complete data.\\n**Cons**: \\\"Amending\\\" an existing checkpoint is new behavior. Need to handle edge cases (no prior checkpoint, push failures). Push on stop adds latency to the agent's shutdown path.\\n\\n### Approach B: Create a supplementary \\\"trailing\\\" checkpoint on Stop\\n\\nOn the Stop hook:\\n1. Generate a new checkpoint ID\\n2. Write a \\\"trailing\\\" checkpoint to `entire/checkpoints/v1` with metadata linking it to the previous checkpoint (e.g., `parent_checkpoint: <id>`)\\n3. Push to remote\\n\\n**Pros**: No mutation of existing checkpoints. Clean append-only semantics.\\n**Cons**: Web UI needs to understand parent/child checkpoint relationships. More complex data model. Two checkpoints for what's conceptually one unit of work.\\n\\n### Approach C: Condense-on-stop with deferred push\\n\\nOn the Stop hook:\\n1. Condense the session to `entire/checkpoints/v1` (either updating the existing checkpoint or creating a new stop-scoped one)\\n2. Don't push immediately — instead, mark a \\\"pending push\\\" flag\\n3. Push happens on next `git push` (PrePush picks it up), OR via a background process/timer, OR via an explicit `entire sync` command\\n\\n**Pros**: No latency on agent shutdown. Eventual consistency.\\n**Cons**: Doesn't solve the \\\"user never returns\\\" problem. Remote stays stale until next push.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### My Recommendation: Approach A\\n\\nApproach A is the cleanest because:\\n- The trailing conversation **is** part of the previous checkpoint — updating it is the semantically