mmits, pushes → cpA1 + cpB pushed to remote\\n3. A commits again (A2) → cpA2 condensed to metadata branch (local only)\\n4. B ends turn → finalizes cpB, pushes → cpB' remote\\n5. A ends turn → needs to finalize both cpA1 and cpA2\\n\\nAt step 5, the intent question is:\\n- cpA1 was already pushed (visible remotely) → we SHOULD finalize cpA1→cpA1' and push it\\n\\n\\n- cpA2 was never pushed → the user hasn't chosen to push yet → we should finalize cpA2→cpA2' but NOT push it\\n\\nSo the user is saying we need per-checkpoint-ID push tracking, not a session-level boolean. But here's the problem: we can't selectively push some commits while leaving others unpushed on the same branch. If we push `entire/checkpoints/v1` to update cpA1', we'd also push cpA2' in the process.\\n\\nThe real question is whether it's acceptable to push cpA2 as a side effect of updating cpA1', even though the user hasn't explicitly chosen to push it. That violates their intent—they may have withheld A2 for a reason. But wait, let me reconsider the actual flow: when B pushes, the entire `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch gets pushed, which already includes cpA1 since it was condensed there by PostCommit. Then when A commits again, cpA2 gets condensed locally, making the local branch ahead of remote by one commit.\\n\\nWhen A ends their turn, both cpA1 and cpA2 get finalized with UpdateCommitted commits, putting the local branch three commits ahead of remote. The problem is that these commits are sequential on the same branch, so pushing cpA1' necessarily means pushing cpA2 and cpA2' as well—there's no way to push just the middle one. This leaves us with a fundamental constraint: either we accept that finalizing the transcript pushes any other unpushed checkpoints on that branch, or we need a different approach.\\n\\nI'm realizing this edge case is pretty rare—it requires multiple active sessions in the same worktree with deliberate decisions about what not to push. But the user's right that it's worth