ug\":\"composed-humming-rocket\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"if we take 1, we potentially get situations where A2 is still local and cpA2' is pushed\\n\\nwhich maybe isn't the end of the world, but it does mean it could be retained as an unattached checkpoint in the corpus if A2 is ever thrown away\"},\"uuid\":\"1be93ede-edbc-4632-9688-75372f8e3c33\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T07:26:32.317Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"default\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"1be93ede-edbc-4632-9688-75372f8e3c33\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/4\",\"sessionId\":\"26fd10e5-9929-4364-b5e7-540290e8931b\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/stop-hook-updates-remote-checkpoints\",\"slug\":\"composed-humming-rocket\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_0168c1MgCPGfxm3t5keuvCYY\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user is pointing out that if we push cpA2' (the finalized checkpoint for A2), but A2 (the actual code commit) is still local and never gets pushed (or gets rebased away, or the branch is deleted), then we'd have an orphaned checkpoint on `entire/checkpoints/v1` that doesn't correspond to any code commit.\\n\\nThis is a valid concern but maybe manageable. Let me think about what the user might be leaning toward...\\n\\nThey said \\\"maybe isn't the end of the world\\\" and \\\"unattached checkpoint in the corpus if A2 is ever thrown away.\\\" They seem to be weighing pragmatism vs purity.\\n \\nI'm exploring a few different strategies to prevent orphaned checkpoints. One idea is to only push on turn-end if certain conditions are met—like checking that all code commits with checkpoints have actually been pushed. But that's tricky to verify reliably. Another angle is tracking which checkpoints were included in a push, then only pushing the turn-end batch if all of the session's checkpoints have already been pushed. Though I'm realizing the original problem might be more fundamental than these conditions can solve.\\n\\nThe real issue is that the finalized transcript needs to be pushed whenever its provisional version was already pushed. So I should track per-checkpoint whether its provisional was included in a push, and use that to decide if finalization is needed. In the edge case, checkpoint A1 got pushed by B's action and needs finalization, but A2 wasn't pushed so it shouldn't trigger a push. The problem is that pushing A1's finalized version would also push A2 as a side effect. What if instead of trying to control when we push at turn-end, I hook into the pre-push phase to finalize any outstanding checkpoints before the push happens?\\n\\nBut that won't work because the turn hasn't ended yet when a push occurs, so sessions are still active. Maybe the real solution is to decouple this: `HandleTurnEnd` records a \\\"needs-push\\\" marker instead of pushing directly, then the next `PrePush` from any push operation picks up those finalized checkpoints. This shifts the staleness window from \\\"until next commit+push\\\" to \\\"until next push.\\\" The downside is it still doesn't handle the case where a user never returns to the session. The core tension is that after turn-end, the remote has only the provisional transcript while the full one stays local, and in multi-session scenarios, one session might have a mix of pushed and unpushed checkpoints.\\n\\nFor the unattached checkpoint risk, the metadata already includes session ID, timestamps, and touched files, so an orphaned checkpoint without a matching code commit is relatively low-risk—it's just transcript data that garbage collection could eventually clean up. This scenario only happens with concurrent active sessions in the same worktree plus specific commit/push timing. The user seems to be weighing these trade-offs and might be ready to accept this as a reasonable compromise.\\n\\nI'm reconsidering the approach more fundamentally—maybe the cleanest solution is to separate finalization from pushing. Finalization (updating the transcript) should always happen at turn-end for any session with checkpoint IDs, which is already working. For pushing, I could track whether a push succeeded during the turn and only push again at turn-end if the remote is still behind, using a simple flag or by recording the remote tracking ref hash after each successful push.\\n\\nThe \\\"unattached checkpoint\\\" issue is inherent to pushing the whole branch and unavoidable without per-checkpoint branches, which would be overengineered. So I should present this as a known trade-off and ask if the user wants to move forward with it.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1400,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":64236,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1400},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYmRsoccK76jJEZSmRkPn\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"c11d4ca6-ab35-49ba-998d-dafd121d2a39\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T07:27:02.724Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"c11d4ca6-ab35-49ba-998d-dafd121d2a39\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/4\",\"sessionId\":\"26fd10e5-9929-4364-b5e7-540290e8931b\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/stop-hook-updates-remote-checkpoints\",\"slug\":\"composed-humming-rocket\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_0168c1MgCPGfxm3t5keuvCYY\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Right. So the real trade-off is:\\n\\n- **Unattached checkpoint in corpus** — cpA2' exists remotely with no corresponding code commit. It's orphaned metadata. Low risk (it's just transcript data), but it's noise that could accumulate.\\n- **Solvable with GC** — a future cleanup pass could prune checkpoints that don't match any commit's `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer. But that's more machinery.\\n\\nLet me reframe where we've landed. We have two separable concerns:\\n\\n1. **Finalization** — updating the transcript on `entire/checkpoints/v1`. Already happens today. Always correct. No change needed.\\n\\n2. **Push** — getting the finalized transcript to the remote. This is where intent vs correctness collides because of branch-level granularity.\\n\\nFor (2), I see three pragmatic landing spots:\\n\\n**A. Accept the leak, push always when flag is set.** Unattached checkpoints are possible but rare (requires concurrent ACTIVE sessions + specific interleaving). Note it as a known limitation. Future GC can clean up.\\n\\n**B. Push only when `TurnCheckpointIDs` has exactly the checkpoints that were pushed.** Track per-checkpoint push status. If all of them were pushed, safe to push. If any weren't, skip. Avoids the leak but means some finalized transcripts stay local longer.\\n\\n**C. Step back entirely** — is there a simpler framing we're missing? For example: does the problem mostly matter for single-session use (the 99% case), and for multi-session we just accept staleness until next explicit push?\\n\\nWhich way are you leaning?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1400,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":64236,\"output_tokens\":1563,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1400,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYmRsoccK76jJEZSmRkPn\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"f171eef5-8fa2-4a90-b356-253524ddc971\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T07:27:10.709Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"f171eef5-8fa2-4a90-b356-253524ddc971\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/w